DOC.HEAD: Soybeans Lead Crop Futures Lower In Thin Trading
DOC.TEXT: Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, paced by moderate losses in the soybean market linked in part to the closing of the Panama Canal. But Anne Frick, senior oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said the decline in soybean prices mostly represented a continuation of a seasonal trend. Trading activity was very light, with many traders getting an early start on the holiday weekend. The Panama Canal was closed to traffic Wednesday as U.S. armed forces launched a surprise assault in Panama in an attempt to capture Panamian leader Manuel Noriega. Shipments of U.S. soybeans to Japan pass through the Panama Canal. But Anne Frick, senior oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said the closing of the canal was ``a pretty minor factor'' in the market's decline. ``It certainly is premature to think any serious or permanent export disruption would be caused by it,'' she said. Soybean prices had slipped lower in the two previous trading sessions. At the close, wheat futures were unchanged to 1 cent lower with the contract for delivery in March at $4.13\ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.38{ a bushel; oats were { cent to } cent lower with March at $1.52 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 5 cents lower with January at $5.74\ a bushel.
